revision.text:
[[File:Vesijako.jpg|thumb|right|Lake [[Vesijako]] in [[Padasjoki]], [[Finland]]]] A '''bifurcation lake''' is a [[lake]] that has outflows into two different [[drainage basin]]s and thus the [[drainage divide]] cannot be defined exactly because it is situated in the middle of the lake.
==Examples== [[Vesijako]] (the name ''Vesijako'' actually means "drainage divide") and [[Lummene]] in the [[Finnish Lakeland]] are two nearby lakes in [[Finland]]. Both drain in two directions: into the [[Kymijoki]] basin that drains into the [[Gulf of Finland]] and into the [[Kokemäenjoki]] basin that drains into the [[Gulf of Bothnia]].
Similarly the lakes [[Isojärvi (Satakunta)|Isojärvi]] and [[Inhottu]] in the [[Karvianjoki]] basin in the [[Satakunta]] region of western Finland both have two outlets: from Inhottu the waters flow into the Gulf of Bothnia through the Eteläjoki River in [[Pori]] and into lake Isojärvi through the Pomarkunjoki River. From lake Isojärvi the waters flow to the Gulf of Bothnia through the Pohjajoki river in Pori and through the Merikarvianjoki river in [[Merikarvia]]. In the Karvianjoki basin there have formerly been two other bifurcations, which no longer exist due to human action.
Another example is [[Bontecou Lake]], a shallow, man-made bifurcation lake in [[Dutchess County, New York]].<ref name="watersheds">{{cite report|author=Dutchess County Environmental Management Council|title=Natural Resource Management Plan for the Wappinger Creek Watershed|publisher=Village of Wappingers GulfFalls|url=http://www.wappingersfallsny.gov/pdf/Natural%20Resource%20Planning.pdf|pages=1, 60|accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref>
[[Lake Diefenbaker]] in [[Saskatchewan]] is a reservoir created by damming [[South Saskatchewan River]] and [[Qu'Appelle River]]. The lake continues to drain into the two rivers, but the Qu'Appelle receives a much enlarged flow (in essence, a diversion of flow from the South Saskatchewan) due to the damming. Both rivers eventually drain into [[Hudson Bay]] via [[Lake Winnipeg]] and the [[Nelson River]].{{cn|date=October 2018}} Also located in Saskatchewan is [[Wollaston Lake]], which is the source of [[Fond du Lac River (Mackenzie River)|Fond du Lac River]] draining into the [[Arctic Ocean]] and of [[Cochrane River (Canada)|Cochrane River]] draining into [[Hudson Bay]] and the Atlantic Ocean.{{cn|date=October 2018}}
[[Isa Lake]] in [[Yellowstone National Park]] is a natural bifurcated lake which drains into two oceans. Its western drainage is to the [[Gulf of Mexico]] (part of the Atlantic Ocean) via the [[Firehole River]], while its eastern drainage is to the [[Pacific Ocean]] via the [[Lewis River (Wyoming)|Lewis River]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}
